# Capability Slots

A **Capability Slot** is a job Equerry can do — holding a conversation, reading an
image, transcribing speech — and you decide which [provider](/docs/add-a-provider)
fills each one. This is the heart of the bring-your-own-backend idea: instead of a
single fixed model, you wire a local Ollama to chat and, in time, a strong
multimodal model to vision, on-device speech to transcription, and so on. Each slot
points at exactly one provider profile, and one profile can fill more than one
slot.

## The slots

In v0.1 only the **Chat** slot is wired and ready to use. The remaining slots are
visible in the app but marked **coming soon** — they are part of the design and
will light up in later releases:

- **Chat** — conversational replies. **Available now.**
- **Vision** — image understanding. *Coming soon.*
- **Speech-to-text** — speech to text. *Coming soon.*
- **Text-to-speech** — text to speech. *Coming soon.*
- **OCR** — text from images. *Coming soon.*
- **Embeddings** — vector indexing. *Coming soon.*

## Map a provider to Chat

Open the **Capability slots** screen. If nothing is mapped yet, the **Chat** slot
shows a banner prompting you to **"Map a provider to CHAT"**.

1. Tap the **Chat** slot.
2. A picker lists every provider profile you have saved. Select the one you want
   Chat to use.
3. Tap **Map provider**.

The Chat slot now shows the provider and model it is mapped to. To change it later,
tap the slot again and pick a different profile. That is the whole setup loop:
install Equerry, set it as your assistant, add a provider, and route Chat to it.

## What's next

The other slots will become available as Equerry grows. When they do, mapping them
works exactly like Chat — open the slot, pick a provider, map it — so the workflow
you just learned carries straight over.
